TY  - JOUR
T1  - Making Use of Difference: Diversity, Debate, and Decision Comprehensiveness in Top Management Teams
AU  - Simons, Tony
AU  - Pelled, Lisa Hope
AU  - Smith, Ken A.
Y1  - 1999/12/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256987
DO  - 10.5465/256987
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 662
EP  - 673
VL  - 42
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study examined how top management team diversity variables and debate interacted to influence two measures of company financial performance. Further, it assessed the degree to which decision comprehensiveness mediated those interaction effects. Multi-informant data from the top management teams of 57 manufacturing companies revealed that more job-related types of diversity interacted with debate to influence financial performance, but a less job-related type (age diversity) did not. Decision comprehensiveness partially mediated those effects.
AB  - This study examined how top management team diversity variables and debate interacted to influence two measures of company financial performance. Further, it assessed the degree to which decision comprehensiveness mediated those interaction effects. Multi-informant data from the top management teams of 57 manufacturing companies revealed that more job-related types of diversity interacted with debate to influence financial performance, but a less job-related type (age diversity) did not. Decision comprehensiveness partially mediated those effects.
